      "role": "user",
      "content": "the wand thing makes sense for a quick visual, but i need to be a bit more specific for the exam questions. i've heard professors call it 'spooky action at a distance' a lot. can you explain why it's described that way specifically? how is it 'spooky' compared to just knowing that if i have two socks, one red and one blue, and i pick up a red one, the other one must be blue?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the term 'spooky action at a distance' was coined by Albert Einstein, who was quite puzzled by the idea. He found it 'spooky' because it seemed to violate the very fabric of his understanding of the universe. In the classical world, if you have a pair of socks, one red and one blue, and you pick up the red one, the other sock being blue is a simple matter of probability. But with quantum entanglement, it's as if the socks are whispering to each other, telling the other sock, \"Hey, I'm red, so you must be blue!\" No matter how far apart they are, the entangled socks seem to communicate instantly, defying the usual rules of space and time. This 'spooky' connection is not just a matter of knowing the other sock's color; it's as if the socks are entangled in a dance, moving in perfect harmony, even when they're separated by vast distances. It's a mysterious and fascinating phenomenon that challenges our classical understanding of the world.",
